    <title>Combined summary - Feedback requested: "reject" p2p message</title>
    <updated>2023-06-07T18:45:45.508581+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2013-October/003479.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The context discusses various email conversations related to the Bitcoin network, with discussions revolving around different issues and proposals. One of the main topics discussed is the problem of transactions not propagating properly, which led to bug reports in the bitcoinj library. Luke-Jr suggests that handling a peer that doesn't relay a transaction should be expected behavior, emphasizing the importance of handling nodes that do not relay transactions for any reason.The use of HTTP codes for success messages in the Bitcoin protocol is also discussed. It is suggested that they could extend the HTTP scheme on their own if needed. However, it was advised against using fixed-length strings or enums as they make it harder to extend without any benefit.In another conversation, the issue of reject categories for Bitcoin transactions is discussed. Gavin Andresen proposes adding new reject codes for the Bitcoin protocol, with specific categories to organize them. However, there was agreement that using HTTP codes directly would not be a good fit for the Bitcoin protocol, and using varints for reject codes was unnecessary since it was unlikely that more than sixteen would ever be needed.There are also discussions about the possibility of using nVersion as a soft-forking mechanism. Peter Todd suggests rejecting blocks with unexpected nVersions to prevent them from using nVersion as a soft-forking mechanism. However, he notes that this results in a hard fork, which he believes is wrong and undermines Bitcoin's security model.Throughout the context, links to relevant resources such as upcoming Intel webinars and a white paper on secure code signing practices for Android apps are provided. Additionally, the importance of handling nodes that do not relay transactions for any reason, including if they lie about having done so, is emphasized.</summary>
